# Rust patterns

Recipes that show up repeatedly. Pair with `design.md` (the principles)
and `code-smells.md` (what each pattern fixes). The canonical catalogue
is the community
[Rust Design Patterns](https://rust-unofficial.github.io/patterns/)
book — read it before inventing your own.

## Newtype

Wrap a primitive in a `struct` that's a different type. Free at runtime,
priceless at compile time.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash)]
pub struct UserId(u64);

impl UserId {
    pub fn new(raw: u64) -> Self { Self(raw) }
    pub fn as_u64(self) -> u64 { self.0 }
}

// Now `fn charge(order: OrderId, customer: UserId)` cannot have its
// arguments accidentally swapped.
```

Use newtypes for: IDs, money amounts, percentages, durations measured in
specific units, anything domain-meaningful.

For domain value objects with invariants, validate in the constructor:

```rust
pub struct Email(String);

impl Email {
    pub fn parse(s: &str) -> Result<Self, EmailError> {
        if !s.contains('@') { return Err(EmailError::Malformed); }
        Ok(Self(s.to_owned()))
    }
    pub fn as_str(&self) -> &str { &self.0 }
}
```

A constructed `Email` is guaranteed valid.

## Builder

For structs with many configuration knobs.

```rust
pub struct HttpClient { /* … */ }

pub struct HttpClientBuilder {
    timeout: Option<Duration>,
    retries: u32,
    base_url: Option<Url>,
}

impl HttpClientBuilder {
    pub fn new() -> Self { Self::default() }
    pub fn timeout(mut self, d: Duration) -> Self { self.timeout = Some(d); self }
    pub fn retries(mut self, n: u32) -> Self { self.retries = n; self }
    pub fn base_url(mut self, u: Url) -> Self { self.base_url = Some(u); self }
    pub fn build(self) -> Result<HttpClient, BuildError> { /* validate, construct */ }
}
```

Pair with **type-state** when invariants matter — e.g.
`HttpClientBuilder<MissingUrl>` → `HttpClientBuilder<HasUrl>` so
`.build()` only exists when required fields are present.

## RAII guards

Tie cleanup to a value's lifetime. The destructor runs even on panic.

```rust
pub struct MutexGuard<'a, T> { /* … */ }
impl<'a, T> Drop for MutexGuard<'a, T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) { /* release the lock */ }
}
```

Use for: locks, transaction commits/rollbacks, file handles, timers,
spans/instrumentation. If you find yourself writing `try`/`finally`
patterns by hand, you want an RAII guard.

## Strategy via enum dispatch

When you have a small, closed set of strategies, prefer an enum to a
trait object.

```rust
enum Compression {
    None,
    Gzip { level: u32 },
    Zstd { level: i32 },
}

impl Compression {
    pub fn compress(&self, input: &[u8]) -> Vec<u8> {
        match self {
            Compression::None => input.to_vec(),
            Compression::Gzip { level } => gzip(input, *level),
            Compression::Zstd { level } => zstd(input, *level),
        }
    }
}
```

When the set is open or implementations live in many crates, reach for
`Box<dyn Trait>` instead.

## Visitor / sealed trait

When a trait is meant to be implemented only inside your crate (so you
can add methods without breaking downstream), use the sealed-trait
pattern:

```rust
pub trait Renderer: private::Sealed {
    fn render(&self, doc: &Document) -> String;
}

mod private { pub trait Sealed {} }
```

## Result chains and `?`

Chain failable operations linearly. `?` lifts compatible errors
automatically when `From` is implemented.

```rust
fn process(path: &Path) -> Result<Summary, Error> {
    let text = std::fs::read_to_string(path)?;       // io::Error -> Error
    let doc = parse(&text)?;                         // ParseError -> Error
    let summary = summarise(&doc)?;
    Ok(summary)
}
```

Avoid building error states "by hand" with `.map_err(|e| ...)` unless
you genuinely need to translate.

## `From`/`Into` for ergonomic constructors

```rust
impl From<&str> for ProjectName { fn from(s: &str) -> Self { /* … */ } }
```

Callers can `let name: ProjectName = "foo".into();` — and `?` benefits
when `From` is implemented for error conversions.

## Iterator adapters

Express data transformations as chained adapters. Skip the temporary
`Vec`s.

```rust
let total: u64 = orders.iter()
    .filter(|o| o.is_paid())
    .map(|o| o.total_cents)
    .sum();
```

For accumulator logic that doesn't map to existing combinators, use
`fold`.

## `Cow` for borrow-or-own

When most callers can pass a borrowed slice but the function occasionally
needs to allocate (e.g. to normalise):

```rust
fn normalise(s: &str) -> Cow<'_, str> {
    if s.chars().all(|c| c.is_lowercase()) {
        Cow::Borrowed(s)
    } else {
        Cow::Owned(s.to_lowercase())
    }
}
```

## Composition root

A single function (usually `main` or a `bootstrap` module) wires the
concrete types into the generic application code.

```rust
fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let cfg = Config::from_env()?;
    let repo = SqlxOrderRepo::connect(&cfg.db)?;     // concrete
    let app = App::new(repo);                        // generic over R: OrderRepository
    app.run()
}
```

No other module decides "which database" — they only declare what they
need (a trait bound).
